        -:   32:
        -:   33:/*!
        -:   34:  \class SoIndexedFaceSet SoIndexedFaceSet.h Inventor/nodes/SoIndexedFaceSet.h
        -:   35:  \brief The SoIndexedFaceSet class is used to handle generic indexed facesets.
        -:   36:
        -:   37:  \ingroup coin_nodes
        -:   38:
        -:   39:  Facesets are specified using the coordIndex field. Each face must be
        -:   40:  terminated by a negative (-1) index. Coordinates, normals, materials
        -:   41:  and texture coordinates from the current state (or from the
        -:   42:  vertexProperty node if set), can be indexed to create triangles,
        -:   43:  quads or polygons.
        -:   44:
        -:   45:  Here's a usage example of just about the simplest possible use of
        -:   46:  this node, to show a single polygon face:
        -:   47:
        -:   48:  \verbatim
        -:   49:  #Inventor V2.1 ascii
        -:   50:  
        -:   51:  Separator {
        -:   52:     Coordinate3 {
        -:   53:        point [ 0 0 0, 1 0 0, 1 1 0 ]
        -:   54:     }
        -:   55:     IndexedFaceSet {
        -:   56:        coordIndex [ 0, 1, 2, -1 ]
        -:   57:     }
        -:   58:  }
        -:   59:  \endverbatim
        -:   60:
        -:   61:  Binding PER_VERTEX_INDEXED, PER_VERTEX, PER_FACE_INDEXED, PER_FACE
        -:   62:  or OVERALL can be set for material, and normals. The default
        -:   63:  material binding is OVERALL. The default normal binding is
        -:   64:  PER_VERTEX_INDEXED. When PER_VERTEX_INDEXED binding is used and the
        -:   65:  corresponding materialIndex, normalIndex, texCoordIndex field is
        -:   66:  empty, the coordIndex field will be used to index material, normal
        -:   67:  or texture coordinate. If you do specify indices for material,
        -:   68:  normals or texture coordinates for PER_VERTEX_INDEXED binding, make
        -:   69:  sure your index array matches the coordIndex array: there should be
        -:   70:  a -1 wherever there is a -1 in the coordIndex field. This is done to
        -:   71:  make this node more easily readable for humans.
        -:   72:
        -:   73:
        -:   74:  A fairly common request when rendering facesets is how to display a
        -:   75:  set of faces with different colors on the backside versus the
        -:   76:  frontside. There is not \e direct support for this in the API, but
        -:   77:  it can easily be implemented by duplicating all faces in both the
        -:   78:  SoShapeHints::COUNTERCLOCKWISE and the SoShapeHints::CLOCKWISE
        -:   79:  order. Here is a simple usage example, showing the technique for a
        -:   80:  single polygon, using two SoFaceSet nodes for rendering the same
        -:   81:  polygon from both sides:
        -:   82:
        -:   83:  \verbatim
        -:   84:  #Inventor V2.1 ascii
        -:   85:  
        -:   86:  Separator {
        -:   87:     Coordinate3 { point [ 0 0 0, 1 0 0, 1 1 0 ] }
        -:   88:  
        -:   89:     Separator {
        -:   90:        Material { diffuseColor [ 1 1 0 ] }
        -:   91:        ShapeHints {
        -:   92:           vertexOrdering COUNTERCLOCKWISE
        -:   93:           shapeType SOLID
        -:   94:        }
        -:   95:        FaceSet { numVertices [ 3 ] }
        -:   96:     }
        -:   97:  
        -:   98:     Separator {
        -:   99:        Material { diffuseColor [ 1 0 0 ] }
        -:  100:        ShapeHints {
        -:  101:           vertexOrdering CLOCKWISE
        -:  102:           shapeType SOLID
        -:  103:        }
        -:  104:        FaceSet { numVertices [ 3 ] }
        -:  105:     }
        -:  106:  }
        -:  107:  \endverbatim
        -:  108:
        -:  109:  The same effect can also be done in the following manner, using an
        -:  110:  SoIndexedFaceSet to explicitly render the polygon coordinates in
        -:  111:  both directions (clockwise and counterclockwise):
        -:  112:
        -:  113:  \verbatim
        -:  114:  #Inventor V2.1 ascii
        -:  115:  
        -:  116:  Separator {
        -:  117:     Coordinate3 { point [ 0 0 0, 1 0 0, 1 1 0 ] }
        -:  118:  
        -:  119:     Material { diffuseColor [ 1 0 0, 1 1 0 ] }
        -:  120:     MaterialBinding { value PER_FACE_INDEXED }
        -:  121:  
        -:  122:     ShapeHints {
        -:  123:        vertexOrdering COUNTERCLOCKWISE
        -:  124:        shapeType SOLID
        -:  125:     }
        -:  126:  
        -:  127:     IndexedFaceSet {
        -:  128:        coordIndex [ 0, 1, 2, -1, 2, 1, 0, -1 ]
        -:  129:        materialIndex [ 0, 1 ]
        -:  130:     }
        -:  131:  }
        -:  132:  \endverbatim
        -:  133:
        -:  134:
        -:  135:  Another rather rare issue that might be interesting to know about is
        -:  136:  that to render polygons with concave borders, you should set up an
        -:  137:  SoShapeHints node with SoShapeHints::faceType set to
        -:  138:  SoShapeHints::UNKNOWN_FACE_TYPE in the scene graph before the
        -:  139:  SoIndexedFaceSet (or SoFaceSet) node. This needs to be done to force
        -:  140:  the rendering code to tessellate the polygons properly to triangles
        -:  141:  before sending it off to OpenGL. Without it, the polygons will be
        -:  142:  sent as-is to OpenGL, and the OpenGL implementation's tessellator is
        -:  143:  often not able to tessellate properly. Here is an example which
        -:  144:  usually fails without the SoShapeHints node (try commenting it out,
        -:  145:  and see what happens):
        -:  146:
        -:  147:  \verbatim
        -:  148:  #Inventor V2.1 ascii
        -:  149:  
        -:  150:  ShapeHints { faceType UNKNOWN_FACE_TYPE }
        -:  151:  
        -:  152:  Coordinate3
        -:  153:  {
        -:  154:          point [ 2 0 0,
        -:  155:                  1 0 0,
        -:  156:                  1 1 0,
        -:  157:                  0 1 0,
        -:  158:                  0 2 0,
        -:  159:                  1 2 0,
        -:  160:                  2 2 0,
        -:  161:                  2 1 0 ]
        -:  162:  }
        -:  163:  
        -:  164:  FaceSet {}
        -:  165:  \endverbatim
        -:  166:
        -:  167:  <b>FILE FORMAT/DEFAULTS:</b>
        -:  168:  \code
        -:  169:    IndexedFaceSet {
        -:  170:        vertexProperty NULL
        -:  171:        coordIndex 0
        -:  172:        materialIndex -1
        -:  173:        normalIndex -1
        -:  174:        textureCoordIndex -1
        -:  175:    }
        -:  176:  \endcode
        -:  177:
        -:  178:  \sa SoFaceSet, SoIndexedTriangleStripSet
        -:  179:*/
        -:  180:
